</i>, <i>whelrihte</i> ‘wheelwright, maker of wheels and wheeled vehicles’ (Old English <i>hwēol</i> + <i>wyrhta</i>). See also   Wheeler  .","History: John Wheelwright (<i>c.</i> 1592–1679), clergyman, came to Boston, MA, from Lincolnshire, England in 1636. He was banished from Massachusettes for his support of his sister-in-law, Anne Hutchinson, in the antinomian controversy; he set up a community at Exeter, NH."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Greek: the Lord gave graciously; whom Jehovah gave; whom Jehovah bestowed."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":7,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When John Thomas Wheeler was born in 1375, in Cranfield, Bedfordshire, England, his father, Sir John Wheeler, was 27 and his mother, Sussanah Milk, was 28. He married Elizabeth Mary Phillips in 1397, in Cranfield, Bedfordshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1420, in his hometown, at the age of 45, and was buried in Shrewsbury, Shropshire, England."},"et":{"1375–1420":"1375–1420","1377